{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 13:43:37.697012", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nScope and goal\n- Assess the current network health and identify any abnormal behavior.\n- Localize faulty devices / subsystems and determine most likely root cause(s).\n- I used host-level reachability tests and device network/routing state (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route / OSPF) collected from the environment and the FRR routers.\n\nHigh-level summary / overall health\n- Core/distribution routing (OSPF) has converged and the core routers exchange adjacencies. The OSPF topology and routes for the customer subnets (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24) and the 10.200.0.0/24 server farm network are present on the FRR routers.\n- User hosts obtain addresses (DHCP appears working) and can reach DHCP server, DNS (10.200.0.2), the public-facing web servers (10.200.0.3–.6) and the load balancer (10.200.0.7).\n- The backend web subnet 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0..2) is reachable locally among the backend hosts and to the load balancer, but is not reachable from the rest of the network and backend hosts cannot reach some infrastructure in 10.200.0.0/24 (DNS/web servers).\n- This results in partial isolation of backend_web_* hosts: they can reach/load-balance through the load balancer but cannot reach the rest of the server farm/infrastructure and are not visible in the global routing domain.\n\nKey observations and evidence\n1) OSPF / routing (FRR routers)\n- The core routers (router_core_1/2/3) and distribution routers show 10.200.0.0/24 in their routing tables (advertised via server_access_router). Example: router_core_3 lists:\n  - \"O>* 10.200.0.0/24 [110/20] via 172.16.0.11, eth2 ...\"\n- There is no route for 20.200.0.0/24 in the FRR routing outputs collected from the core routers. I did not find any OSPF advertisement or kernel route for 20.200.0.0/24 on the FRR routers.\n  - Expected (per network description) — \"All infrastructure and server networks are advertised by FRR OSPF\" — is not true for 20.200.0.0/24.\n\n2) Host and server interface/routing state\n- server_access_router: 10.200.0.1/24 is locally connected (br0) and is advertising/serving 10.200.0.0/24.\n- load_balancer:\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24\n  - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24\n  - route table shows 20.200.0.0/24 as directly connected on the load_balancer only.\n- backend_web_0..2:\n  - Have addresses in 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0: 20.200.0.2; backend_web_1: 20.200.0.3; backend_web_2: 20.200.0.4).\n  - Their default gateway is 20.200.0.1 (the load balancer).\n\n3) Ping / reachability matrix (selected results)\n- Hosts -> load_balancer and hosts -> web_server_0..3 and hosts -> dns_server: OK (0% loss).\n  - Example: host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7): 0% loss.\n- Hosts -> backend_web_1 and backend_web_2: 100% loss from the hosts.\n  - Example: host_1_1_1_1 -> backend_web_1 (20.200.0.3): 100% loss.\n- Hosts -> backend_web_0: some tests reported \"unknown\" (no data returned), effectively not reachable from hosts.\n- backend_web_* -> load_balancer: OK (0% loss).\n  - backend_web_0/1/2 -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7): 0% loss.\n- backend_web_* -> web_server_* and backend_web_* -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): 100% loss.\n  - Example: backend_web_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): 100% loss.\n- load_balancer -> dns_server: OK (0% loss).\n\nInterpretation / abnormal behavior\n- The 20.200.0.0/24 network (backend web servers) is present only locally on the load_balancer and backend_web hosts: it is not advertised into the network OSPF domain and therefore not present in the core routing tables.\n  - Evidence: FRR/router routing tables include 10.200.0.0/24 but not 20.200.0.0/24.\n- Backend hosts (20.200.0.0/24) can reach the load balancer but cannot reach hosts in 10.200.0.0/24 (DNS and web servers). Conversely, hosts in 10.200.0.0/24 cannot reach backend_web_* directly.\n  - Evidence: pings from backend_web_* to dns_server fail, while load_balancer can reach dns_server.\n- The load_balancer sits at the boundary between 10.200.0.0/24 and 20.200.0.0/24, but traffic from backend_webs to 10.200.0.0/24 does not traverse (or is not forwarded/translated) — backend_web->dns/server pings show 100% loss even though the backend default route points to the load_balancer and the load_balancer itself can reach those servers.\n  - This indicates the load_balancer is allowing traffic to/from itself to 10.200.0.0/24 but is not forwarding or otherwise enabling traffic originated from the 20.200.0.0/24 hosts into the 10.200.0.0/24 network (or return traffic is not delivered back to the backends).\n- The observed isolation is consistent across multiple backend hosts, so the problem is at the network boundary (load_balancer or routing/advertisement), not a single backend host.\n\nFault localization (most likely faulty devices / subsystems)\n1) Primary: load_balancer (network/routing role)\n- The load_balancer is the only device with an interface in both 10.200.0.0/24 (eth0) and 20.200.0.0/24 (eth1). Backend hosts use it as next-hop.\n- Symptoms point to the load_balancer failing to forward/route traffic between its eth1 (20.200.0.0/24) and eth0 (10.200.0.0/24) for traffic sourced by backends — pings from backends to DNS fail, while pings from the load_balancer itself to DNS succeed.\n- Possible misconfigurations evidenced by data: IP forwarding disabled on load_balancer, firewall or iptables rules dropping transit, or lack of route advertisement of 20.200.0.0/24 from any routing device. (I am only identifying likely faults, not remediating.)\n\n2) Secondary: FRR / routing advertisement (server_access_router or router-hosting OSPF)\n- 20.200.0.0/24 is not visible in FRR/OSPF. If policy/requirement is that \"all infrastructure and server networks are advertised by FRR OSPF\" then 20.200.0.0/24 is missing from OSPF advertisements and kernel route tables on the routers. The server_access_router has 10.200.0.1/24 but no interface or advertisement for 20.200.0.0/24.\n- If the design expectation was that 20.200.0.0/24 should be part of the routed domain, the device that should advertise it (server_access_router or another FRR-speaking router) is not configured with that subnet.\n\nLikely root cause(s)\n- Top-level root cause: the backend network 20.200.0.0/24 is isolated from the FRR/OSPF routing fabric and is reachable only on the load_balancer. Consequently:\n  - There is no network-wide route to 20.200.0.0/24 (no FRR advertisement).\n  - Even though the load_balancer is multi-homed (10.200 + 20.200), it is currently not acting as a router/forwarder between those subnets for traffic from/to backend hosts (or is blocking/isolating backend-originated traffic). This prevents backend_web_* hosts from reaching DNS and other 10.200.0.0/24 hosts, and prevents other hosts from directly reaching backend_web_*.\n- The observed behavior could be intentional (security/isolation) or accidental (misplaced backend hosts on a private 20.200 net without routing), but it contradicts the stated expectation that \"All infrastructure and server networks are advertised by FRR OSPF so that hosts can resolve and access the web services end-to-end.\" The absence of 20.200.0.0/24 in OSPF/routing indicates a configuration/advertisement gap.\n\nAdditional supporting detail (selected facts)\n- host_1_1_1_1: IP 10.1.1.10, default via 10.1.1.1 — host can reach DNS (10.200.0.2), load_balancer (10.200.0.7), and web servers (10.200.0.3..6).\n- load_balancer: 10.200.0.7/24 (eth0) and 20.200.0.1/24 (eth1) — shows both networks locally, route table contains both networks.\n- backend_web_1 <-> backend_web_2: can reach each other (20.200 intra-subnet connectivity is fine).\n- backend_web_1 -> load_balancer: OK; backend_web_1 -> dns_server: 100% loss.\n- FRR routers (router_core_1/2/3) show 10.200.0.0/24 routes via server_access_router; no 20.200.0.0/24 route visible.\n\nConclusions (diagnostic)\n- The environment has one clear connectivity anomaly: the backend web subnet (20.200.0.0/24) is isolated from the OSPF/routed fabric and cannot reach or be reached by 10.200.0.0/24 servers (except via the load_balancer itself). The isolation is functionally manifested as:\n  - Hosts and core routers do not have a route to 20.200.0.0/24.\n  - Backend hosts cannot reach DNS and cannot reach 10.200.0.0/24 servers despite having a default gateway pointing to the load balancer.\n- Localization points to the load_balancer and the server/router-side advertisement of 20.200.0.0/24 as the components responsible for the isolation:\n  - Either the load_balancer is not forwarding/translating traffic from 20.200.0.0/24 into 10.200.0.0/24, or\n  - The 20.200.0.0/24 network was never intended to be routed (intentionally isolated) but the stated design expectation that infrastructure networks are advertised is not satisfied.\n- OSPF and core routing otherwise appear healthy and converged for the advertised networks (10.* and 10.200.0.0/24).\n\nNotes / items to verify next (for troubleshooting, not remediation)\n- Confirm whether 20.200.0.0/24 is intended to be isolated (policy) or intended to be part of the routed domain.\n- On load_balancer:\n  - Verify IP forwarding/sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward and check firewall rules (iptables/nft) that might block forwarding between eth1 and eth0.\n  - Confirm whether the load_balancer is expected to advertise 20.200.0.0/24 into OSPF (if it runs FRR) or whether another router should host/advertise that network.\n- On server_access_router or FRR routers:\n  - Check configuration to confirm whether 20.200.0.0/24 should be present and, if so, why it is not being advertised.\n- If the network design intentionally keeps backend_web hosts unreachable from the host subnets, confirm that current behavior matches security expectations (but the initial network description suggested all server networks should be advertised).\n\nEnd of diagnostic report.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 27614, "output_tokens": 5776, "total_tokens": 33390, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 0}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3072}}}
